Great first skip!

I thought the tests proceeded in a natural way, and I was interested to see what the results would be each time.

I really  don't think you need Dr. Cotton's note at the very end. Everything he says seems pretty clearly conveyed by the incident report just before. I would also swap the final two paragraphs of the Incident Log, so the last line of the article is  The material/structural changes are way less emotionally engaging than what happened to the Site-19 personnel, and should not be the final thing in the reader's mind, when the human wreckage created by the ill-advised and understaffed test is the real tragedy. Floors and ceilings can be replaced.

Otherwise, swell work! +1!





